          "body": "The third scene introduces women weeping for Tammuz at the north gate of the LORD's house (8:14). Tammuz was the Babylonian-Sumerian god of vegetation and fertility, whose annual death and descent into the underworld were lamented in a liturgical mourning ceremony tied to the agricultural calendar. The rite originated in Mesopotamia; its presence in the Jerusalem temple gate reveals how thoroughly Babylonian religion had penetrated the capital's worship even before the exile. The fourth scene is the climax: twenty-five men positioned between the temple porch and the altar — the most sacred outdoor space of the complex, where the priests made daily burnt-offerings — with their backs to the temple and their faces bowed toward the rising sun (8:16). The physical posture is the theological statement. To turn one's back to the house of YHWH while prostrating to the sun is not confused syncretism; it is deliberate inversion. The sun-cult had deep roots in Egypt and Mesopotamia, and the twenty-five may represent the priestly college or royal council. The worst possible people, in the worst possible posture, in the worst possible location. The escalation the refrain promised has been delivered."
