        "excerpt": "To the north of the altar gate was this idol of jealousy at the entrance... so that I would be far from My sanctuary.",
        "body": "The first exhibit in the divine tour requires only two verses to present, but those verses carry the entire chapter's theological weight in compressed form. The 'idol of jealousy which provokes to jealousy' (semel ha-qinah, 8:3, 5) is positioned 'at the entrance' — not hidden, not in a back room, but at the north gate, visible to every worshiper entering the inner court. Its public placement suggests it had official sanction, likely during the reign of Manasseh (2 Kings 21:7 records that Manasseh 'set the carved image of Asherah in the house') or its aftermath.\n\nYHWH's commentary on the scene is what makes it theologically irreducible: 'the great abominations which the house of Israel are committing here, so that I would be far from My sanctuary' (8:6). The idol's function, whatever the worshipers intended, is to drive YHWH out of His own house. The covenant category operative here is jealousy (qinah) — the same term used in the Decalogue for YHWH's response to Israel's worship of other gods (Exodus 20:5). In the Hebrew prophetic tradition, Israel's relationship with YHWH is a marriage covenant; idolatry is adultery; the idol installed at the temple gate is the other lover installed in the marital home.\n\nThe divine question 'do you see what they are doing?' (8:6) is not a request for information. YHWH already sees with perfect comprehensiveness. The question is forensic and rhetorical — it demands that Ezekiel, and through him the exile community, register the offense with the same gravity God does. This rhetorical device recurs throughout the chapter (vv. 12, 15, 17) and becomes the chapter's prosecutorial rhythm: look at this, see it clearly, now see something worse.\n\nThe refrain 'yet you will see still greater abominations' (8:6) signals that the first exhibit, serious as it is, does not yet exhaust Israel's guilt. The chapter's argument requires escalation — each scene must surpass the previous one in covenantal offensiveness — so that the verdict of total, unmitigated divine wrath in 8:18 is proportionate to the evidence. The refrain is the chapter's structural spine."
