        "excerpt": "Son of man, do you see what the elders of the house of Israel are committing in the dark?... their backs to the temple of the LORD and their faces toward the east.",
        "body": "The second through fourth abominations form the chapter's lengthy central section and share a common logic: each one represents a successive tier of Israel's leadership structure, each in a successive layer of sacred space, each practicing a successive form of covenant-abandonment.\n\nThe second scene (8:7-13) is introduced with a theatrical directive: Ezekiel is commanded to dig through the wall himself, to find the hidden entrance to the inner chamber. This participatory archaeology mimics the act of divine exposure — God is breaking through the wall of Israel's concealment, and Ezekiel's physical digging enacts what the vision is doing spiritually. Inside, the walls are covered with Egyptian-style animal iconography — remes (creeping things), behemah (beasts), and sheqets (detestable things) from the Levitical unclean-animal lists (Leviticus 11) — the full panoply of what Torah had declared ritually abominable. Standing before these images are seventy elders with censers, burning incense. The number seventy is the full council number (cf. Exodus 24:1; Numbers 11:16); the representative completeness is the point. Their stated theology — 'The LORD does not see us; the LORD has forsaken the land' — is the interpretive center of the entire chapter. Practical atheism is the engine beneath every visible apostasy. Once a community is convinced that God is absent or indifferent, no ritual boundary remains effective.\n\nThe third scene (8:14-15) is the briefest: women weeping for Tammuz at the north gate. Tammuz (Sumerian Dumuzi) was the shepherd-god whose annual death and descent to the underworld were mourned in liturgical lamentation ceremonies associated with the dry season. The rite was pervasive in Mesopotamian religion and had evidently spread westward into Judah. Its significance in the tour is its provenance: this is Babylonian religion — the religion of the captor — practiced inside the house of the Israelite God. The exile that was meant to separate Israel from Babylonian pollution has failed; Babylon has already come to Jerusalem.\n\nThe fourth scene (8:16-17) is the chapter's crescendo. Between the porch and the altar — the most restricted sacred zone, accessible only to priests performing their duties — twenty-five men prostrate themselves toward the east with their backs to the temple. Sun-worship (*shemesh*) had been explicitly prohibited in Deuteronomy 4:19 and 17:3 as one of the paradigmatic apostasies. The posture — backs to the sanctuary, faces to the rising sun — is not confused syncretism but deliberate inversion. John Calvin noted that this scene represents the complete overturning of Israel's covenant orientation: every element of direction, posture, and location says the opposite of what covenant worship required. The enigmatic 'twig to the nose' (8:17) may reflect an additional ritual gesture of contempt — some interpreters follow ancient versions that read it as 'sending the branch to My nose,' a form of ritual insult to YHWH Himself. Whether the gesture is an insult or a rite, it functions in the text as the final, unbearable accumulation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maskit* (carved image, 8:12) — from a root meaning 'to look,' probably an image designed to attract a deity's gaze. *Tammuz* appears only here in the Hebrew Bible. *Shachah* (prostrating/worshiping, 8:16) is the standard Hebrew verb for physical worship — its use for sun-worship in the temple's holy zone is the climax of the chapter's irony."
